{{Infobox building |image=File:Wheat Street Baptist Church.JPG |caption=Wheat Street Baptist Church seen from the north (back side) |coordinates = {{coord|33.7551682|-84.3756783|display=inline}} |map_type=Atlanta |map_caption = <center>location in [[Intown Atlanta]]</center> | start_date = 1920 | completion_date = 1931 }}
'''Wheat Street Baptist Church''' is located at 359 Auburn Ave. in the [[Sweet Auburn]] neighborhood of [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. The building is part of the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Historic District]]; the church and its leader at the time, Rev. [[William Holmes Borders]], played a leading role in the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref>{{cite book|last=English|first=James W. |title=The prophet of Wheat Street: the story of William Holmes Borders, a man who refused to fail|publisher=D. C. Cook Pub. Co.|year=1967|isbn=978-0-912692-19-7}}</ref> The congregation dates back to 1869, with the present building dating from 1921. From 1898-1929, Rev. [[P. James Bryant]] served as pastor.<ref>[http://wheatstreet.org/?page_id=57 "Our History", 'Wheat Street Baptist Church]</ref>
